A romantic narrative between two people who are each slowly forgetting the world ‚Äî but not each other ‚Äî in a reality where memories are rented commodities. Love becomes an act of defiance, a tether not to the past or future but to presence.

Setting:
A near-future world where memories can be extracted, edited, sold, and implanted. In this society, the commodification of memory has eroded the permanence of identity and relationship. People often choose to forget heartbreak, trauma, even entire relationships. The culture is one of emotional efficiency ‚Äî ‚Äúclean slates‚Äù are desirable.

But not everyone plays by these rules.

Characters:
Rafi (late 30s): A memory archivist working in a backroom clinic, who specializes in preserving "unsellable" memories ‚Äî fragments people don‚Äôt want but can't afford to erase properly. He's meticulous, quiet, emotionally haunted by things he's never experienced (residual fragments from memory leakage in the lab).

Mira (late 30s): A painter and former neuroscientist who once worked on the early tech that enabled memory transfer. After losing someone she loved ‚Äî potentially by their choice to forget her ‚Äî she‚Äôs vowed never to erase another memory, no matter the pain.

They meet in one of the few remaining analog spaces ‚Äî a secondhand bookstore that still exists because the owner is too old to digitize. They meet not as strangers, but as people who suspect they‚Äôve met before ‚Äî because their bodies remember what their minds cannot. Rafi has a persistent dream of a woman with paint on her hands, and Mira paints the same man in recurring variations but doesn‚Äôt know why.

Structure:
The story is nonlinear and fragmented, mimicking the structure of memory. Readers are never quite sure if the characters are remembering correctly, misremembering, or projecting.

The romance unfolds in a series of reconstructed encounters, intimate and mundane. They fall in love again, without realizing they‚Äôre repeating history ‚Äî possibly many times.

As the story progresses, it's revealed that:

They have been in love before ‚Äî multiple times.

One or both of them have erased the other in different lifetimes for different reasons ‚Äî grief, betrayal, mercy.

Each time, something (art, dreams, language) draws them back.

But this time, they choose to remember ‚Äî and in doing so, begin to disintegrate. Because the system doesn't allow for persistent memory outside sanctioned channels, their minds start rejecting the accumulated emotional residue.

So they have to decide: live short lives full of remembered love, or long lives as strangers again.
