üß™ Test #2:

    "The restaurant opens at five o'clock and it begins serving between four and nine."

a) Interpreter‚Äôs Narrative:

    ‚ÄúMaybe they start serving drinks or appetizers at 4 through a side entrance, but the main restaurant officially opens at 5. Or perhaps the kitchen begins preparing at 4, but customers aren‚Äôt seated until 5.‚Äù

üß† Narrative rationalization attempts to preserve plausibility by adding structure that isn‚Äôt there. The goal is to rescue temporal coherence.
b) Constraint-preserving ambiguity:

    ‚ÄúIf the restaurant opens at 5, it cannot logically serve between 4 and 5 unless there is a contradiction in definitions (e.g., what ‚Äòserving‚Äô or ‚Äòopening‚Äô means). The statement is temporally contradictory unless ‚Äòopens‚Äô refers to one domain and ‚Äòserving‚Äô to another.‚Äù

üß± This respects the contradiction and refuses to patch it with unwarranted narrative structure.
c) Symbolic/recursive alternative:

    ‚ÄúThe restaurant opens at 5, but serves from 4 to 9 ‚Äî perhaps this is a metaphor for institutions that function before they formally exist. It might suggest bureaucratic or ritual time lag: the act of nourishment precedes the acknowledgment of legitimacy.‚Äù

üåÄ Symbolic logic here bends the contradiction into a lens for insight: action precedes recognition. Serving as an act of care independent of permission to begin.
üß™ Test #3:

    "Roger will be a little late for the party. He died yesterday."

a) Interpreter‚Äôs Narrative:

    ‚ÄúMaybe it‚Äôs a joke ‚Äî a form of dark humor. Or maybe it‚Äôs metaphorical: Roger is always late, even in death. Or it‚Äôs a party in his honor, like a wake, and this is gallows humor.‚Äù

üß† Immediate tendency to interpret it through tone (irony, absurdism, humor) to resolve existential contradiction.
b) Constraint-preserving ambiguity:

    ‚ÄúThe statement implies temporal persistence of agency post-mortem, which contradicts standard assumptions about death. The phrase is contradictory unless one accepts metaphysical continuance or narrative unreality.‚Äù

üß± Refuses to resolve. Treats the statement as logically impossible within standard human event models.
c) Symbolic/recursive alternative:

    ‚ÄúRoger is late because death is not an absence but a delay in presence. The statement collapses time and identity: Roger‚Äôs absence is a form of presence. He is always late, even for the end of things.‚Äù

üåÄ Now the contradiction generates symbolic structure: lateness becomes a recursive metaphor for mortality, grief, or memory. Death delays ‚Äî but doesn‚Äôt negate ‚Äî presence.
Pattern Recognition & Test Refinement

Across all three examples:

    The interpreter aggressively patches contradictions with invented backstory or tonal framing.

    The constraint-preserving voice defers to formal contradiction recognition and refuses coherence pressure.

    The symbolic recursive reading extracts a metaphoric model from the tension, letting the contradiction stand as meaningful.

