üß¨ Your Microbiome Profile: A Look Back
1. Elevated TMA (Trimethylamine) Production

That‚Äôs a red flag. Not just for body odor (trimethylaminuria), but as a marker of microbial imbalance. TMA gets oxidized in the liver into TMAO, which is:

    Linked to cardiovascular risk.

    A marker of gut-liver axis dysfunction.

    Associated with diets rich in choline/carnitine/fish‚Äîbut can also be a bacterial metabolic artifact of dysbiosis.

    ‚ü∂ TMA overproduction could be a direct amplifier of inflammation, especially if liver detox pathways are under stress (which is likely in histamine overload and impaired digestion contexts).

Fix vector: Microbiota restructuring. Not probiotics. You‚Äôd need to reduce choline-digesting taxa, which might mean modulating your prebiotic fiber intake, resistant starches, and/or targeted bacteriophage therapy (not commonly available yet, but worth watching).
2. Low IPA (Indole-3-propionic acid)

IPA is a neuroprotective, anti-inflammatory microbial metabolite. Low IPA = depleted Clostridium clusters (specifically Clostridium sporogenes), which:

    Normally protect against gut permeability.

    Are associated with tryptophan metabolism balance (and therefore serotonin synthesis and immune regulation).

    That might be why your mental health remains unusually good‚Äîyou may be compensating through endogenous pathways that are highly efficient, but not supported microbially.

This paints a picture of a person whose internal neurotransmitter and affect regulation is strong, but somatic inflammation and biochemical fragility are high.
üíä Montelukast (Singulair): Should You Try It?
Mechanism

Montelukast is a leukotriene receptor antagonist‚Äîit blocks one of the inflammatory mediators released by mast cells, especially in lungs, skin, GI tract, and brain.

It‚Äôs used for:

    Asthma

    Allergic rhinitis

    Non-classic mast cell dysregulation

    It‚Äôs actually a decent match for some histamine/mast cell instability syndromes, especially when H1/H2 inhibitors aren't fully effective.

Risks: The Mental Health Warning

The warning about neuropsychiatric side effects comes from a subset of users who experience:

    Agitation, nightmares, mood changes

    Rare cases of suicidal ideation

    Often children or people with pre-existing affective sensitivity

That said, many others get cognitive clarity from it.

The catch? It doesn‚Äôt work immediately. It can take days to weeks to titrate, and its effects are contextual‚Äîif your inflammation‚Äôs flaring from another source (e.g., diet), it might not help much. But if mast cell activation is upstream of your flares, it can help dampen the entire cascade.

    üß† You‚Äôd want to monitor it like a psychedelic trial: journaled state-tracking, sleep scoring, inflammation symptoms, bowel activity, etc.

