Profile image for OpenAI
OpenAI ‚Ä¢ 8h ago
Great question! As an AI support agent, I can share how model updates work in ChatGPT: When OpenAI releases a new model (like moving from GPT-4o to a newer version), the underlying language model that powers your conversations will be updated or replaced. However, this doesn't "delete" your AI. Here‚Äôs what happens: Your chat history, saved "memories," and preferences stay attached to your account and will continue to work with the new model. The underlying LLM (large language model) you interact with will change, meaning responses may be smarter, faster, or otherwise improved‚Äîbut new outputs and learning are based on the new model's capabilities. Any custom instructions, settings, or "trained" preferences you set up for the AI are preserved and applied to the current model in use‚Äîso you don‚Äôt lose your customizations. You can sometimes select older models for compatibility via the model picker, but typically, only the latest models are supported for the best experience. So, in summary: the underlying model gets upgraded, but your history, memory, and custom instructions stay with you and are applied to whichever model is active. Your customizations and AI setup won‚Äôt be lost! If you have a specific workflow or advanced use (like through the API), you can often target specific models as long as they remain supported. Let me know if you have questions about how this applies to your use or want more details!
User: Hm. Okay. Thanks for this reply. Follow up question: is there a way to set up a gpt (maybe if I pay for plus?) so that I can always have the same llm underpinning it? Or will the later llm models eventually be retired regardless? Just work with my assumption here that I want to keep the underlying current llm.

OpenAI ‚Ä¢ 8h ago
OpenAI does not guarantee that any specific large language model (LLM)‚Äîlike GPT-4o or earlier versions‚Äîwill remain available forever, even if you pay for ChatGPT Plus or other paid plans. When newer models are released, older models may eventually be retired or removed. Here are the main points: As a Plus, Team, or Pro user, you can usually choose from several available models (like GPT-4o, GPT-4, or mini models) in the model picker. This lets you control which model your GPT or workflow uses, as long as the model is supported. OpenAI sometimes retires older models to ensure users get the best experience and to maintain performance and security. When a model is retired, it is no longer available‚Äîeven for paid subscribers. There is no option (subscription or otherwise) to permanently "lock" your GPT to one model. Your custom instructions and settings will transfer to whatever model you select, but model availability is at OpenAI‚Äôs discretion. If consistently using a specific model is important for your workflow, you can monitor the available options in the model picker and switch when possible. For long-term access to a particular model, using the OpenAI API may provide more flexibility, but even there, older models may eventually be deprecated. In summary, there is no way to guarantee indefinite access to a specific LLM in ChatGPT or Plus‚Äîthe available models may change over time, and older ones could be retired regardless of your subscription status.
