Profile image for OpenAI
OpenAI ‚Ä¢ 8h ago
You can give read and write access to your GitHub repositories through ChatGPT and OpenAI tools, but there are important details and some limitations: 1. ChatGPT (web/app product):- Using features like Deep Research (available with Plus, Pro, and Team plans), you can connect ChatGPT to your GitHub repositories. You do this by authorizing ChatGPT to access specific repositories via the GitHub connector.- Once authorized, ChatGPT can read (pull in code and documentation) from those repositories.- Write access: When you authorize the connector, you choose the level of access (read or write) for each repository. If you grant write access, ChatGPT can do things like suggest and generate pull requests as part of certain workflows (like with ChatGPT Codex for Enterprise and advanced coding features).- This is managed securely‚Äîyour interaction is outside the context of a traditional "app" integration, but you still connect an official OpenAI/ChatGPT connector to GitHub (uses OAuth, and GitHub‚Äôs permission system). 2. Custom GPTs:- Regular (consumer) custom GPTs in ChatGPT cannot directly commit code or perform write operations to GitHub on their own.- For advanced use (like automatic commits), you‚Äôd use Codex in ChatGPT Enterprise and connect with GitHub using the official Connector. Codex can read from and write to repositories you‚Äôve authorized, including creating pull requests and making code changes if write permissions are allowed. 3. API / Custom Apps (for Developers):- If you‚Äôre building with the OpenAI API, your app is responsible for handling interactions with GitHub by using the GitHub API. The model never interacts directly; your code (or server) reads from and writes to GitHub, sends relevant data to the LLM, and handles any commit/push actions. Summary:- You can allow ChatGPT or Codex (mainly on Enterprise/Team/Pro/Plus with the Deep Research or enterprise coding features) to have read and/or write access by connecting with the GitHub connector and setting permissions.- Write access requires explicit authorization.- "No app" in the traditional sense, but you must connect using the official ChatGPT/GitHub integrations. 
